05674nam a22007455i 9780774822626DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20122012xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748226267 a10.59962/97807748226262doi  a(DE-B1597)661993  a(OCoLC)797815276  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1029b.R66 2012 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a327.7122300aRooted Cosmopolitanism :bCanada and the World /ced. by Kathryn Walker, Will Kymlicka. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (252 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tRooted Cosmopolitanism: Canada and the World -- tThe Theory of Rooted Cosmopolitanism -- tCosmopolitanism and Patriotism -- tA Defence of Moderate Cosmopolitanism and/or Moderate Liberal Nationalism -- tUniversality and Particularity in the National Question in Quebec -- tRooted Cosmopolitanism: Unpacking the Arguments -- tWe Are All Compatriots -- tThe Practice of Rooted Cosmopolitanism -- tCosmopolitanizing Cosmopolitanism? Cosmopolitan Claims Making, Interculturalism, and the Bouchard-Taylor Report -- tA World of Strangers or a World of Relationships? The Value of Care Ethics in Migration Research and Policy -- tThe Doctrine of the Responsibility to Protect: A Failed Expression of Cosmopolitanism -- tClimate Change and the Challenge of Canadian Global Citizenship -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCanadians take pride in being good citizens of the world, yet our failure to meet commitments on the global stage raises questions. Do Canadians need to transcend national loyalties to become full global citizens? Is the very idea of rooted cosmopolitanism simply a myth that encourages complacency about Canada's place in the world? In this volume, leading scholars assess both in theory and practice the concept of rooted cosmopolitanism, using Canada as a test case. They show that local identities such as patriotism and Quebec nationalism can, but need not, conflict with cosmopolitan principles. Local ties enable and impede Canada's global responsibilities in areas such as multiculturalism, climate change, immigration and refugee policy, and humanitarian intervention. By examining how Canada has negotiated its relations to "the world" both within and beyond its own borders, Rooted Cosmopolitanism evaluates the possibility of reconciling local ties and nationalism with commitments to human rights, global justice, and international law.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCosmopolitanismzCanada. 0aCosmopolitanism. 0aInternationalism. 0aNationalismzCanada. 0aWorld citizenship. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAbu-Laban, Yasmeen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdelman, Howard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlattberg, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKymlicka, Will, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKymlicka, Will, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLenard, Patti Tamara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaehlke, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchaffer, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTan, Kok-Chor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThériault, Joseph-Yvon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWalker, Kathryn, eco